lines.line: > The speaker is introduced and begins by discussing her upbringing in Arlington County, where she attended Yorktown High School. Despite her initial disinterest in attending college, preferring to pursue a career in professional figure skating, her mother encouraged her to apply to George Mason College. She eventually enrolled, choosing psychology as her major due to her interest in the subject from high school, despite the college not offering a psychology major at the time.

metadata.title: Introduction and Early Life

Despite her initial disinterest in attending college, preferring to pursue a career in professional figure skating, her mother encouraged her to apply to George Mason College. lines.line: > The speaker elaborates on her decision to attend George Mason College, influenced by her mother's suggestion as a way to extend her high school experience. She recalls her first days at the college, including the formation of a carpool with friends from her neighborhood and her initial social interactions on campus.

metadata.title: College Decision and Initial Experience
metadata.synopsis: The speaker elaborates on her decision to attend George Mason College, influenced by her mother's suggestion as a way to extend her high school experience. She recalls her first days at the college, including the formation of a carpool with friends from her neighborhood and her initial social interactions on campus.

lines.line: # Social Life and Activities at College

> The speaker describes her early college social life, which revolved around her carpool group and included attending parties and social gatherings. She mentions the vibrant social scene that extended to Georgetown due to the lower drinking age at the time, and the mix of fun and serious discussions about the Vietnam War during these gatherings.

lines.line: # Academic Experience and Shift in Political Views

> While academics came easily to the speaker, her focus was not on her studies but rather on the social aspects of college life. She discusses how her views on the Vietnam War evolved over time, initially supporting the war but later becoming a vocal opponent as her understanding of the war's implications deepened.

lines.line: > The speaker details her active participation in the anti-Vietnam War movement, including organizing vigils and demonstrations. She recounts her arrest during a protest at a draft board, her subsequent trial, and the legal battle that reached the United States Supreme Court, reflecting on the principles of nonviolence that guided her actions.

metadata.title: Anti-Vietnam War Activities and Arrest

lines.line: > The speaker shares her journey into the feminist movement, sparked by attending a women's liberation meeting. This experience profoundly influenced her, leading her to embrace radical feminist ideals and actively participate in discussions and activities promoting women's rights during her college years.

metadata.title: Feminism and Women's Rights
metadata.synopsis: The speaker shares her journey into the feminist movement, sparked by attending a women's liberation meeting. This experience profoundly influenced her, leading her to embrace radical feminist ideals and actively participate in discussions and activities promoting women's rights during her college years.

lines.line: > The speaker recalls significant protests on campus, particularly in response to the shooting at Kent State University, which deeply affected the student body. She also discusses her encounters with FBI surveillance, criticizing the administration's cooperation with the FBI in monitoring student activities, which she learned through obtaining her FBI file.

metadata.title: Campus Protests and FBI Surveillance
metadata.synopsis: The speaker recalls significant protests on campus, particularly in response to the shooting at Kent State University, which deeply affected the student body. She also discusses her encounters with FBI surveillance, criticizing the administration's cooperation with the FBI in monitoring student activities, which she learned through obtaining her FBI file.

lines.line: > After college, the speaker pursued a career in journalism, influenced by a mentor at George Mason. She reflects on the significant changes at George Mason University over the years, noting her mixed feelings about its expansion but also recognizing familiar aspects of the campus during a recent visit. She concludes by mentioning her donation of personal papers to Virginia Commonwealth University, highlighting her ongoing commitment to documenting her activist and professional experiences.
